The 1965 Immigration and Nationality Act is where everything starts. Before that, the U.S. basically welcomed only white European immigrants. Asians were very few and faced strict limits. After 1965, the U.S. began prioritizing high education and professional skills for immigration. For the first time, America opened its doors to skilled talent from around the world.

For India, this change was huge. Before 1965, there were only about ten thousand Indian immigrants in the whole country. After the reform, large numbers of highly educated doctors, engineers, and scholars came to the U.S. They became the foundation of the Indian American community, and their background shaped the groupâ€™s overall education and income levels.

Before that, the Chinese immigrant population was very mixed in background, came through many different pathways: early Chinese Americans born in the U.S., refugees from Southeast Asia, highly educated migrants from Taiwan, and later students and economic migrants from mainland China. This created a very diverse group with big differences in class and background. Chinese Americans were never a single â€œfilteredâ€ elite group, but a mix of many historical and political waves.

Because of this, Chinese Americans show a â€œhigh peak + long tailâ€ pattern: many highly educated professionals, but also many who arrived as refugees or working-class migrants. This isnâ€™t about ability, itâ€™s a result of different immigration routes.

Put simply, the differences we see today come from when and how each group came to the U.S., not from culture or â€œtalentâ€, despite many people believe.

People really need to stop asking whether this is a bull market or a bear market. That mindset is straight out of the 1990s. The market does not care about your labels. Bitcoin especially does whatever it wants while people keep trying to name it like a pet.

Since the October high we have been in a correction. That is obvious. What is not obvious is how big that correction becomes or when it ends. Corrections are messy. They stretch, they fake, they look bullish one week and heavy the next. You do not get a clear moment where a bell rings and someone declares the new trend. That only exists in hindsight and in clickbait videos.

If you actually want to know what the market is doing, watch the structure. Are the rallies impulsive or just weak three-wave bounces. Are supports holding or bleeding. Are we still pushing higher highs or slowly losing strength. That is the stuff that matters. Not whether someone finally slaps the word bull or bear on the chart so people can feel safe again.

If your whole plan depends on giving the market a name, you are already behind. The winners watch behaviour. The losers wait for labels.
